1
00:00:01,500 --> 00:00:04,000
This game is entirely controlled by a
machine learning model.

2
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:06,200
I've let it play the game multiple times

3
00:00:06,500 --> 00:00:09,000
and it ended up learning how to score
points by itself.

4
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:11,200
We call this approach reinforcement
learning, and

5
00:00:11,200 --> 00:00:13,200
we'll go through all the steps to make

6
00:00:13,200 --> 00:00:16,000
a model that can play this game, or
even other games.

7
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:19,000
I'll first explain the problem that we
will solve.

8
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:22,000
Reinforcement learning comprises two
main components:

9
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:24,000
the *environment*, in this case a
2D game,

10
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:27,000
and the *agent*, here, a spaceship in
that game.

11
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:31,000
The agent interacts with the environment
by moving around and firing projectiles.

12
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:34,000
It obtains rewards that indicate how
good its actions are.

13
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:39,000
If the agent collects a point or hits
an enemy, it obtains a positive reward.

15
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:42,000
If it gets blasted by an enemy, it
obtains a negative reward.

16
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Our goal is to maximize the rewards to
make the agent

17
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:46,000
as good at playing as possible.

18
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:49,000
By the way, you can try that game out
if you want.

19
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Open up the project on Github, clone the
repository on your machine,

20
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:55,000
install the dependencies, and run
the game.

21
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:57,500
Let's now have a look a models that
we can use.

22
00:00:57,500 --> 00:01:01,000
A basic model for reinforcement learning
is the Q-table.

23
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:05,000
"Q" stands for "quality", which is an
estimation of the future rewards that

24
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
an agent can obtain for a given state
and action.

25
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
A Q-table looks like this. The rows
represent all possible states of

26
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:14,500
the environment, and the columns
represent the possible actions that

27
00:01:14,500 --> 00:01:18,000
an agent can perform. Each cell contains
a Q-value.

28
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:22,000
Actions that are more likely to lead to
rewards are given a higher Q-value.

29
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:26,000
For instance, in this state, moving
towards the collectible is more likely

30
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:29,000
to result in a future reward than
moving away from it,

31
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:33,000
so moving in this direction corresponds
to a higher Q-value.

32
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:36,000
When playing the game, the agent can
look up the Q-table to

33
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
perform the action with the best quality
given some state of the environment.

34
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:43,000
Q-tables are easy to understand, but
often impractical.

35
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:47,000
Before using them, they have to be
filled by performing each action

36
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:50,000
in all possible states of the
environment and determining

37
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:51,500
the corresponding Q-values.

38
00:01:51,500 --> 00:01:54,000
That works for simple environments, but
for more complex problems,

39
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:58,000
we may have to try millions of states
and actions to fill a Q-table.

40
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,000
This approach would not work well in
these cases,

41
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:04,000
but we can improve it. Instead of using
a large table,

42
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:07,000
we can approximate it with a machine
learning model.

43
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:09,000
This is called Deep Q-learning.

44
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:13,000
The model will not memorize all possible
states and actions like a Q-table,

45
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:16,000
but will rather learn patterns from
interactions with the game to estimate

46
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,000
which actions are more likely to result
in rewards.

47
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:21,000
This is more scalable than a Q-Table
because it can

48
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:26,000
generalize to unseen states, making it
more suitable for complex environments.

49
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:30,000
We will use an artificial neural
network for this approximation model.

50
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,000
As the name tells, neural networks are
made individual neurons, like this one.

51
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:39,000
It's a mathematical model that takes
one or multiple values as inputs,

52
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:41,000
multiplies each input by a weight,

53
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:44,000
sums the weighted inputs along with a
bias term,

54
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,000
and applies a mathematical operation to
the result.

55
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,500
This operation is called the activation
function, and it's used

56
00:02:50,500 --> 00:02:53,000
to make the neuron model more complex
patterns.

57
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:56,000
An example of a simple but widely used
activation function is

58
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:00,000
the rectified linear unit, which cancels
negative values.

59
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:03,000
The training process modifies the
parameters of the neuron -

60
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,000
that is, its weights and bias, to make
it learn how to play the game.

61
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:11,000
A single neuron is pretty limited, but
we can create more complex models by

62
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:13,000
connecting neurons into a neural
network.

63
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:16,500
These networks are often organized into
layers of neurons that

64
00:03:16,500 --> 00:03:20,500
take the information from the previous
layer and transmit it to the next layer.

65
00:03:20,500 --> 00:03:24,500
In our case, the first layer of the
network, the input layer, receives

66
00:03:24,500 --> 00:03:28,500
footage of the game. The final layer,
the output layer, decides

67
00:03:28,500 --> 00:03:32,500
which button to push. This is used to
control the agent on the screen.

68
00:03:32,500 --> 00:03:36,000
Between these, we can add hidden layers,
which help the network

69
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
learn complex patterns from the input.

70
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:40,000
We can change the number of hidden
layers,

71
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,000
the number of neurons in each layer,

72
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:44,000
and the way that neurons are connected.

73
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:47,000
All of these changes are examples of
hyperparameters,

74
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:51,000
which are settings that define the
architecture of the model.

75
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:55,000
In theory, we could simply flatten the
input image into a 1D vector

76
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:57,000
and feed it to a layer of neurons.

77
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
This model is called a multilayer
perceptron.

78
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,000
It's a good approach for many problems,
but multilayer perceptrons often

79
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:07,000
struggle with images because they lack
spatial awareness.

80
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:10,000
They treat the pixels of the image as
unrelated, separate entities,

81
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:14,000
which is not effective. In practice,
if you want to understand an image,

82
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
you have to look at collections of
pixels to

83
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:20,000
recognize particular features, like
shapes or edges.

84
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:23,000
We can do that with convolution, a
mathematical operation where

85
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
a small grid - the kernel - slides
across the image to detect features.

86
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:29,000
For instance, a Sobel operator is

87
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:32,000
a type of convolution that
highlights edges.

88
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:37,000
In our model, the convolutional layer
will extract relevant features to

89
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:41,000
recognize collectibles and enemies from
the input.

90
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,000
The next stage is a fully connected
layer.

91
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:47,000
The features extracted by the
convolutional layer are flattened

92
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:51,000
into a one-dimensional vector and fed
to all neurons of that layer.

93
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:55,000
During training, the parameters of the
neurons will be adjusted to decide

94
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
which actions must be performed
depending on the detected features.

95
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Finally, we can plug the fully
connected layer to the output.

96
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:05,000
This neural network can be written with
the following PyTorch code.

97
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:08,000
The network will probably not be good
at playing because

98
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:12,000
it is pretty shallow - meaning that it
doesn't have many layers.

99
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:15,000
Research has shown that increasing the
depth of a neural network, that is,

100
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:19,000
increasing its number of layers, can
improve its performances.

101
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:22,000
But we have to be careful not to add
too many layers because

102
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:26,000
we then run the risk of overfitting the
model, which means that it will

103
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:29,000
memorize specific examples seen during
training instead of developing

104
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:31,000
a general understanding of the game.

105
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:34,000
Let's summarize: we want to train a
reinforcement learning agent

106
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,000
that will learn to play the game.

107
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:39,000
We can do that by filling a Q-table and
letting the agent look up

108
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:41,000
the best action to take for any state.

109
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:44,000
That table would be large and
impractical, so we instead

110
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:47,000
approximate it. This approach is known
as Deep Q-learning,

111
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:51,000
and the neural network that is used is
called a Deep Q-Network.

112
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:53,000
The next step is to train this network.

113
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:57,000
For now, its parameters are left at
their default values.

114
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Here's what happens when we let the
untrained model play.

115
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:03,000
As expected, it performs poorly because
it still hasn't learned

116
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:06,000
the rules of the game. Here's how
we'll train it:

117
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:11,000
We create an environment and make the
agent play. This is called an episode.

118
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:15,000
Episodes are split in discrete steps,
which are game frames.

119
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:18,000
On each step, the model observes a 2D
image from the game and

120
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,000
predicts a Q-value for all actions.

121
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:23,000
In other words, it tries to guess the
propensity of each action

122
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,000
to lead to rewards. The agent then

123
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:28,000
performs the action with the best
Q-value, which

124
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:30,000
modifies the environment and may result
in a reward, positive or negative.

125
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:32,000
The agent collects the reward

126
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:34,000
and observes the new state of the
environment.

127
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:38,000
The model then predicts the Q-values
for this new state and

128
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:42,000
selects the highest Q-value. This
represents the future reward that the

129
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:46,000
agent expects to obtain by performing
this action in a subsequent step.

130
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:49,000
We now add up the reward that the agent
just collected with the future reward

131
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:53,000
that it expects to obtain. This is
called the Bellman equation.

132
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,000
It estimates the quality of an action
not just from the immediate reward,

133
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:59,000
but also from the future rewards that
it expects to get.

134
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:02,000
Our goal is to make the model estimate
the Bellman equation

135
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:04,000
as well as possible to identify the
actions that lead to

136
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:07,000
the highest rewards.

137
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:10,000
To do that, we want to minimize the
difference between

138
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:13,000
the Q-value predicted before the action,
and the Q-value calculated

139
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:17,000
after performing the action and taking
the reward into account.

140
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:20,000
We call this difference the loss.

141
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:23,000
The loss is propagated in the network
in the inverse direction

142
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:26,000
to compute gradients, which are,
roughly speaking,

143
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:29,000
values that indicate how the parameters
need to be adjusted to minimize

144
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:35,000
the loss. The process that computes
gradients is called backpropagation.

145
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:37,000
We then use the gradients retrieved
during backpropagation

146
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:42,000
to adjust the parameters of the network
with a process called gradient descent.

147
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:46,000
This makes the model slightly better at
approximating the Bellman equation.

148
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:49,000
Steps are repeated until the episode
ends, either by losing or reaching

149
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:53,000
the maximum number of steps. Once the
episode ends, a new one begins,

150
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:55,000
and the process continues until the
model approximates

151
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:00,000
the Bellman equation to our
satisfaction.

152
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:05,000
This graph shows the performances of
the model over its training.

153
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:09,000
The X-axis shows the number of episodes
and the Y-axis shows the average score

154
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:12,000
obtained by the agent when we evaluate
it between episodes.

155
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:16,000
The model gradually improves, but its
performances are very unstable.

156
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:19,000
We can improve the training process to
stabilize and enhance the performances

157
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:23,000
of the model. Here are the 5 main
improvements I've added:

158
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:26,000
First improvement: Add randomness
during training.

159
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:31,000
This is called exploration - we choose
actions that the neural network

160
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:33,000
would not have otherwise selected on
its own.

161
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:36,000
That way, the model experiments a wider
variety of actions and it becomes

162
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:39,000
better at approximating the Q-table.

163
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:42,000
Exploration contrasts with exploitation,
which is when we use the action

164
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:46,000
selected by the network instead of
picking a random one.

165
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:49,000
We start by relying mostly on
exploration, and as the network becomes

166
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:52,000
better at selecting the right actions,
we gradually

167
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
use more and more exploitation.

168
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:57,000
Second improvement: Downsize the input.

169
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Raw game footage looks pretty small for
a human, but it still contains

170
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:04,000
more than 65 thousand pixels for each
frame. The neural network needs

171
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:08,000
a lot of parameters to process them,
so we can simply downsize the image.

172
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:12,000
The network now needs fewer parameters
and becomes easier to train.

173
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:16,000
Third improvement: Combine frames. The
current model looks at a single frame

174
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:19,000
to decide which action to perform, so
it has a hard time understanding

175
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:23,000
the motion of objects. We can instead
give it multiple frames.

176
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:25,000
That way, it will be able to figure out

177
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:28,000
the direction of projectiles and
collectibles.

178
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:32,000
Fourth improvement: Increase depth. As
we've seen, adding hidden layers

179
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:35,000
in the neural network makes it better
at processing data -

180
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,000
provided that you don't add too many.

181
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:41,000
I've added two convolutional layers -
that will improve performances

182
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,000
without leading to overfitting.

183
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
Fifth improvement: Experience replay.

184
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
Right now, the model is trained on
consecutive steps,

185
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:52,000
which are highly correlated. This is
not ideal because

186
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:55,000
the network might overfit to these
observations.

187
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:58,000
Instead, we can store the observations
in an experience buffer and

188
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:01,000
let the model sample random
observations from the buffer

189
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:04,000
when performing backpropagation and
gradient descent.

190
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:07,000
That way, it is exposed to a varied set
of experiences,

191
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:09,000
which improves its ability to
generalize.

192
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:14,000
Let's recap: we trained a reinforcement
learning model to play a game by itself.

193
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:17,000
The model is a deep Q network that
predicts which actions are more likely

194
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:22,000
to result in rewards, and the agent
uses the predictions to score points.

195
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:25,000
We improved our initial model by using
exploration,

196
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:26,000
modifying the input data,

197
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:30,000
increasing depth, and using experience
replay.

198
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:32,000
These improvements stabilize the
training process and

199
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,000
result in a more efficient model.

200
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:38,000
The training process is not perfect,
though, and in some cases, the network

201
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:40,000
does not learn how to play well.

202
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:44,000
For instance, it may end up learning to
just hide in a corner and spam

203
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:48,000
the fire button. This is called a local
optimum. It's not the best

204
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:52,000
strategy overall, but if the network is
not exposed to a varied set of

205
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:56,000
experiences during its training, it may
learn this strategy at some point and

206
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:00,000
then stick to it instead of exploring
other potentially better solutions.

207
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:04,000
To further improve the model and avoid
local optima, we could, for instance:

208
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:07,000
Use a more advanced model, like a
Dueling Q-Network or

209
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:09,000
recurrent neural network;

210
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:13,000
Optimize the rewards obtained by the
agent to prioritize long-term goals and

211
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:15,000
penalize repetitive actions, or

212
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:19,000
Adjust the hyperparameters of the model
to improve training.

213
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:22,000
There's a lot more to reinforcement
learning than what I've laid out

214
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
in this video, so let me know if you'd
like to see more.

215
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:28,000
Also, I encourage you to read these
papers if you want more information

216
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:30,000
on reinforcement learning.

217
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:32,000
"Playing Atari with Deep Reinforcement
Learning" covers the

218
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:36,000
architecture of deep Q networks and
their training process.

219
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:39,000
"Deep Learning" goes over the
fundamentals of neural networks,

220
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:42,000
including backpropagation and gradient
descent.

221
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:46,000
"ImageNet Classification with Deep
Convolutional Neural Networks" presents

222
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:49,000
a deep learning model for image
classification and

223
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:51,000
explains convolutional layers.

224
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:54,000
Everything required to play the game
and replicate the training is

225
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,000
in my Github repository. Training the
model might take some time,

226
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:00,000
especially if you don't have a
compatible GPU, but

227
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:02,000
I've also made a simpler game that
takes much less time to train,

228
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:05,000
so you can try it even on less powerful
systems.

229
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:07,000
Don't hesitate to check it out.
